@hahla When you install Couchbase from source, you don't have to follow any instructions from the GeoCouch README, it's already bundled. The documentation on how to use GeoCouch on Couchbase is at http://www.couchbase.com/docs/couchbase-manual-2.0/couchbase-views-writing-geo.html

If you've further questions, you can either contact me direcly or as on the Couchbase mailing list [1].

[1] https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/couchbase

@dileepbapat This looks good to me. I'm not sure why this wasn't in 1.3.x. 

Can you create a ticket for this in JIRA https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/COUCHDB ?

Unless someone has some objection, I'll merge this in soon.

The proposal above allows the admin to choose between a whitelisting or a blacklisting approach, but not both. Why not give the admin a choice?

@isaacs I agree in an npm-style app you'd prefer whitelisting to ensure you're not leaking. The original code was a blacklist approach, so that's why I added it as an option.

@benoitc I don't think we are adding a lot of complexity by supporting both. The blacklist means that as a server admin, you can be sure that the important couchdb fields are protected against information leaks, even if users decide, or are allowed, to add their own properties to their _user docs as part of an app that applies only to a specific db.

If the white/blacklist is not directly specified, we use a default config and therefore as devs we are able to keep this current within a specific release, and in a way that we can control when packaging.

Overall I am +1 on whitelisting, and pulling in a default config that's wired into the code for safety. I'm +0 on supporting both options, so let's wrap this up & get it in whichever way we go.

 I'll do some doc notes to go with it, @indutny could you add a test perhaps?
